.TH "TEMPORAL.ZONEDDATETIME.SINCE" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.ZonedDateTime.since \- Temporal.ZonedDateTime.prototype.since()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]since()\f[B]\f[R] method of
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] instances returns a new
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object representing the duration from
another date\-time (in a form convertible by
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from()\f[R]) to this date\-time.
The duration is positive if the other date\-time is before this
date\-time, and negative if after.
.PP
This method does \f[CR]this \- other\f[R].
To do \f[CR]other \- this\f[R], use the \f[CR]until()\f[R] method.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
since(other)
since(other, options)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]other\f[R]
A string, an object, or a \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] instance
representing a date\-time to subtract from this date\-time.
It is converted to a \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] object using the
same algorithm as \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from()\f[R].
It must have the same calendar as \f[CR]this\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]options\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An object containing the options for
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration.prototype.round()\f[R], which includes
\f[CR]largestUnit\f[R], \f[CR]roundingIncrement\f[R],
\f[CR]roundingMode\f[R], and \f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R].
\f[CR]largestUnit\f[R] and \f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R] accept all possible
units.
For \f[CR]largestUnit\f[R], the default value \f[CR]\(dqauto\(dq\f[R]
means \f[CR]\(dqhours\(dq\f[R] or \f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R], whichever is
greater.
For \f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R], the default value is
\f[CR]\(dqnanoseconds\(dq\f[R].
The current date is used as the \f[CR]relativeTo\f[R] option.
Note that using units larger than \f[CR]\(dqhours\(dq\f[R] may make the
duration not portable to other calendars, dates, or time zones.
.SS Return value
A new \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object representing the duration
\f[I]since\f[R] \f[CR]other\f[R] to this date\-time.
The duration is positive if \f[CR]other\f[R] is before this date\-time,
and negative if after.
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]RangeError\f[R]
Thrown in one of the following cases:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]other\f[R] has a different calendar than \f[CR]this\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
Any of the options is invalid.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]other\f[R] has a different time zone than \f[CR]this\f[R], and
\f[CR]largestUnit\f[R] is \f[CR]\(dqdays\(dq\f[R] or above.
.RE
.SH DESCRIPTION
The duration returned is a \(lqhybrid\(rq duration.
This means that the duration\(cqs date portion represents full calendar
days like \f[CR]Temporal.PlainDateTime.prototype.since()\f[R] would
return, while its time portion represents real\-world elapsed time like
\f[CR]Temporal.Instant.prototype.since()\f[R] would return.
This \(lqhybrid duration\(rq approach automatically adjusts for DST and
matches widely\-adopted industry standards like \c
.UR https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc5545
RFC 5545 (iCalendar)
.UE \c
\&.
See below for examples.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Offset transitions
When transitions happen, a day may not have exactly 24 hours.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] start = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2024\-11\-03T01:00:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
\f[B]const\f[R] end = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2024\-11\-04T01:00:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
console.log(end.since(start).toString()); \f[I]// PT25H\f[R]
console.log(end.since(start, { largestUnit: \(dqdays\(dq }).toString()); \f[I]// PT1D\f[R]

\f[B]const\f[R] start2 = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2024\-03\-10T01:00:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
\f[B]const\f[R] end2 = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2024\-03\-11T01:00:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
console.log(end2.since(start2).toString()); \f[I]// PT23H\f[R]
console.log(end2.since(start2, { largestUnit: \(dqdays\(dq }).toString()); \f[I]// PT1D\f[R]
.EE
.PP
For this reason, the returned duration is purely time\-based with no
date portion by default, so that it stays unambiguous.
.SS Different time zones
The time portion of the returned duration is purely based on instants
and is not affected by time zones.
However, if you want to include any date units like \f[CR]day\f[R], then
the start and end must be in the same time zone.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] start = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2024\-11\-03T01:00:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
\f[I]// Peru does not use DST so its offset remains \-05:00 year\-round\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] end = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2024\-11\-04T01:00:00\-05:00[America/Lima]\(dq,
);

end.since(start); \f[I]// PT25H\f[R]
end.since(start, { largestUnit: \(dqdays\(dq }); \f[I]// RangeError: time zones \(dqAmerica/Lima\(dq and \(dqAmerica/New_York\(dq aren\(aqt compatible\f[R]

end.withTimeZone(\(dqAmerica/New_York\(dq).since(start, { largestUnit: \(dqdays\(dq }); \f[I]// P1D\f[R]
end.since(start.withTimeZone(\(dqAmerica/Lima\(dq), { largestUnit: \(dqdays\(dq }); \f[I]// P1D1H\f[R]
.EE
.PP
For more examples about how to use \f[CR]since()\f[R], especially with
rounding, see \f[CR]Temporal.PlainDate.prototype.since()\f[R] and
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainTime.prototype.since()\f[R].
